	painsBodyHtml={`<p>At the center of Sikhi is a sincere and beautiful devotion to the one God — Ik Onkar, the single, formless, eternal Creator. That devotion is lived out daily: in <em>Naam Japna</em>, the loving remembrance of God's name; in honest work; in the radical equality of the gurdwara and the open table of <em>langar</em>, where anyone may eat; and in <em>seva</em>, the selfless service of others. These are noble and worthy ways to honor God, and they are to be deeply respected.</p><p>And yet, within hearts that truly love the one God, there can remain a quiet longing — to be not only a faithful servant, but a personally, tenderly known and beloved child. In Sikhi, liberation is understood to come through God's grace alongside right living, devotion, and the weight of merit across the cycle of rebirth. Many feel the steady pull of that effort. The gentle invitation here is not to set aside love for the one God, but to discover that this same God draws near as a <em>Father</em> — one who offers rest, assurance, and a belonging that is received as a gift of grace, not carried as a burden.</p>`}
